answers.body_markdown:
Well, that is what your declarations state.

    ArrayTP&lt;double,12&gt; eggweights;
    ArrayTP&lt;double,13&gt; donuts;

The type of the first variable is `ArrayTP&lt;double,12&gt;`, while that of the second is `ArrayTP&lt;double,13&gt;`. These are different.

    Stack&lt;int&gt; eggs(12);
    Stack&lt;int&gt; dunkers(13);

The type of the first variable is `Stack&lt;int&gt;`, while that of the second is `Stack&lt;int&gt;`. These are the same.

The `12` and `13` for `eggs` and `dunkers` are parameters for their constructors. Expecting different types to come from that is like expecting different types for the following:

    std::string foo{&quot;hello&quot;};
    std::string bar{&quot;world&quot;};

ArrayTP is a template class that will have a class definition like so:

    template &lt;typename T, size_t const Size&gt;
    class ArrayTP 
    {
        private:
        T Array[Size];
        ...
        public:
        ArrayTP()
        {
        ...
        }
    };

As you can see the size parameter is used for declaring an array of that size (on the stack here). *eggweights* will have an array of 12 elements and *donuts* an array of 13 elements. The compiler generates two different types from the template class definition - one with size 12 and one with size 13.

`Stack&lt;int&gt;` takes no size parameter, only a type. However, the constructor of this class probably has a constructor that takes a integral value for the size. It will have a class definition like so:

    template &lt;typename T&gt;
    class Stack
    {
        private:
        T *Array;
      
        public:
        Stack(size_t size)
        {
            Array = new T[size];
        }
     ...
     }

The compiler generates only one type of class, i.e. `Stack&lt;int&gt;`, and the size is supplied as constructor parameter. So

    Stack&lt;int&gt; eggs(12);
    Stack&lt;int&gt; dunkers(13)

are both Stack objects - one of size 12 and the other of size 13.

Ultimately the difference is that with `ArrayTP` you are supplying the size as a template parameter at compile time while with `Stack` you are supplying it as a constructor parameter at run time. The former will generate different types (ArrayTP&lt;double,12&gt; , ArrayTP&lt;double,13&gt;, etc) from the template definition for different sizes.

